China faces a looming water shortage crisis, with only 60-65% of industrial water recycled compared to 80-85% in developed countries.
Beijing struggles to supply its growing population, leading to consumption quotas and local management.
Despite increased grain production, China remains a net food importer due to shrinking arable land.
The country aims to reduce emissions by 4% annually, but lacks resources for significant reductions.
Water scarcity impacts agriculture and ecosystems, with the Three Gorges Dam opening floodgates to alleviate shortages along the Yangtze River.
Severe drought affects millions, prompting artificial rainfall efforts in Chongqing.
